data_answer: They would have to travel a total of 76.84 miles. I found this answer by using the pythagorean thereom. First, I found the length of a leg, the distance between the group and the camp, which was 60 miles. Then, I found the length of the second leg, the distance between the south pole and the group, which was 15 miles. Next, I found the hypotenuse. The formula for finding this is H squared= A squared + B squared. The length of the Hypotenuse was a total of 61.84 miles. Finally I added the total miles from the group to the south pole, 15 miles, and the total miles from the south pole to camp, 61.84, to get the total milage of 76.84 miles. This trip is a total of 76.84 miles.

label: TRAINING
data_answer:
They have to travel about 76.85 miles.

 

Group to South Pole = 15 miles

 

Group to Camp = 60 miles

 

South Pole to Camp= x

 

 

 

The distance from South Pole to Camp can be solved using the Pythagorean Theorem (a squared + b squared = c squared) (The sum of the squares of the legs of a right triangle is equal to the square of the hypoteneuse.)

 

15 squared + 60 squared = x squared.

225 + 3600 = x squared

3825 = x squared

square root of 3825 =x

x = 61.8465843843--about 61.85 miles

 

(Group to South Pole) + (South Pole to Camp) = Distance

(15 miles) + (South Pole to Camp) = Distance

(15 miles) + (61.85 miles) = Total Distance

(15 miles) + (61.85 miles) = 76.85 miles *2 = total distance = 153.7 miles
